To create a clean architecture project called "filelynk" using Golang, PostgreSQL, and GORM, you'll want to separate your code into three main layers: domain, repository, and service.

Here's a possible directory structure and some sample code to help you get started:

```
filelynk/
  cmd/
    main.go
  domain/
    entities.go
  repository/
    user.go
    file.go
    plan.go
    userplan.go
  service/
    user.go
    file.go
    plan.go
  config/
    config.go
  internal/
    postgre.go
```

1. `cmd/main.go` - This is the entry point of the application:

```go
package main

import (
	"filelynk/config"
	"filelynk/internal"
	"filelynk/repository"
	"filelynk/service"
	"fmt"
)

func main() {
	// Load configuration
	config.Load()

	// Initialize database connection
	db, err := internal.ConnectPostgreSQL()
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println("Failed to connect to the database:", err)
		return
	}
	defer db.Close()

	// Initialize repositories
	userRepo := repository.NewUserRepository(db)
	fileRepo := repository.NewFileRepository(db)
	planRepo := repository.NewPlanRepository(db)
	userPlanRepo := repository.NewUserPlanRepository(db)

	// Initialize services
	userService := service.NewUserService(userRepo)
	fileService := service.NewFileService(fileRepo, userPlanRepo)
	planService := service.NewPlanService(planRepo)

	// Application logic goes here, e.g., HTTP server, user registration & authentication, etc.
}
```

2. `domain/entities.go` - This file holds your entities (structs):

```go
// (Paste your previously designed User, File, Plan, and UserPlan structs here)
```

3. `repository/` - This directory contains the repository interfaces and GORM-based implementations:

```go
// Example for user.go in the repository package
package repository

import (
	"filelynk/domain"
	"gorm.io/gorm"
)

type UserRepository interface {
	FindByID(id int64) (*domain.User, error)
	// ... Other repository methods ...
}

type userRepositoryImpl struct {
	db *gorm.DB
}

func NewUserRepository(db *gorm.DB) UserRepository {
	return &userRepositoryImpl{db: db}
}

func (u *userRepositoryImpl) FindByID(id int64) (*domain.User, error) {
	var user domain.User
	err := u.db.First(&user, id).Error
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	return &user, nil
}

// Implement other repository methods...
```

4. `service/` - This directory contains the service layer, which will handle the business logic:

```go
// Example for user.go in the service package
package service

import (
	"filelynk/domain"
	"filelynk/repository"
)

type UserService interface {
	GetUser(id int64) (*domain.User, error)
	// ... Other service methods ...
}

type userServiceImpl struct {
	userRepo repository.UserRepository
}

func NewUserService(userRepo repository.UserRepository) UserService {
	return &userServiceImpl{userRepo: userRepo}
}

func (u *userServiceImpl) GetUser(id int64) (*domain.User, error) {
	user, err := u.userRepo.FindByID(id)
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	return user, nil
}

// Implement other service methods...
```

5. `config/config.go` - Configuration-related code can be placed here.

6. `internal/postgre.go` - This file contains database connection handling:

```go
package internal

import (
	"filelynk/config"
	"filelynk/domain"
	"fmt"
	"gorm.io/driver/postgres"
	"gorm.io/gorm"
)

func ConnectPostgreSQL() (*gorm.DB, error) {
	dsn := fmt.Sprintf("host=%s user=%s password=%s dbname=%s port=%s sslmode=%s TimeZone=%s",
		config.PostgresHost,
		config.PostgresUser,
		config.PostgresPassword,
		config.PostgresDatabase,
		config.PostgresPort,
		config.PostgresSSLMode,
		config.PostgresTimeZone,
	)
	db, err := gorm.Open(postgres.Open(dsn), &gorm.Config{})
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}

	// Migrate your schema
	err = db.AutoMigrate(&domain.User{}, &domain.File{}, &domain.Plan{}, &domain.UserPlan{})
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}

	return db, nil
}
```

This structure gives you a clean separation of concerns, making it easier to manage your code in the long run. The above examples are just starting points, and you'll need to fill in functionality as per your requirements. Please don't forget to handle errors, security aspects (e.g., hashing and storing passwords), and user/file validation in your application.

Additionally, you may want to incorporate an HTTP server using a framework like Gin or Echo to handle user-facing traffic and expose your application logic through a RESTful API.

Here's a guide to get started with Gin: https://gin-gonic.com/docs/examples/
And here's a guide for Echo: https://echo.labstack.com/guide

Creating a full HTML frontend for IPFS (InterPlanetary File System) is beyond the scope of this platform. However, I can provide you a simple example of an HTML interface that allows you to upload and download files using IPFS.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>IPFS Frontend</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>IPFS File Upload</h1>
    <input type="file" id="fileInput">
    <button onclick="uploadFile()">Upload</button>
    <h2>File uploaded: </h2>
    <p id="uploadedFile"></p>

    <h1>IPFS File Download</h1>
    <input type="text" id="fileHash" placeholder="Enter file hash">
    <button onclick="downloadFile()">Download</button>
    <h2>File content:</h2>
    <pre id="downloadedFile"></pre>

    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ipfs/dist/index.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        const ipfs = new Ipfs({ repo: 'ipfs-' + Math.random() });

        ipfs.once('ready', () => {
            console.log('IPFS Ready');
        });

        async function uploadFile() {
            const fileInput = document.getElementById('fileInput');
            const file = fileInput.files[0];
            const reader = new FileReader();
            reader.onload = async function() {
                const buffer = Buffer.from(reader.result);
                const result = await ipfs.add(buffer);
                document.getElementById('uploadedFile').innerText = result[0].hash;
            };
            reader.readAsArrayBuffer(file);
        }

        async function downloadFile() {
            const fileHash = document.getElementById('fileHash').value;
            const stream = ipfs.cat(fileHash);
            let data = '';
            for await (const chunk of stream) {
                data += new TextDecoder().decode(chunk)
            }
            document.getElementById('downloadedFile').innerText = data;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This example uses the IPFS JavaScript library to upload and download files. You can use this template as a starting point and enhance it according to your requirements. Please note, you may need to whitelist the domain in your browser security settings to allow access to the IPFS API, as some browsers may block it by default.
